<p>Down with fuzzy gray !</p>

<p class="posted">posted by skeeter at September 29, 2004 11:18 AM <a href="001426#c2945">#</a></p>

</div><div id="c2948">

<p>The passage about the humanities cracked me up. I went to a real, self-identified <a href="http://www.whitman.edu">liberal arts college</a> and have spent much time since attempting to explain to geeks who earn twice what I do how <a href="http://www.nomorelyrics.net/song/143475.html">my education</a> has any relevance. I think it&#8217;s a &#8220;dancing about architecture&#8221; issue, to some degree: A fuzzy discipline is hard to justify using the logical, stricter &#8220;techie&#8221; yardstick. A partial and rather fuzzy answer, however, is that everyone has some way&#8212;might we even say, a philosophy?&#8212;of making sense of their world and climbing up the mountain of wisdom: literature is my way. (That sounds a lot like the &#8220;not that there&#8217;s anything wrong with that&#8221; cultural relativism of the humanities profs, doesn&#8217;t it? Hee.) Plus, as I&#8217;ve told you, I used college to study what I loved, and I was happy there. Whether that will satisfy the parents who pay one&#8217;s tuition instead of buying a new car every year for four years&#8230; well, let&#8217;s just hope they&#8217;re the fuzzy sort of parents.</p>

<p>By the way, sociology students get mocked for their major even more than English or philosophy majors do. Just so you know. Don&#8217;t let it dissuade you if that&#8217;s what you want to study.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by Riana at September 29, 2004 05:01 PM <a href="001426#c2948">#</a></p>

